5. English Summary

Armenias Solar Surge: A Transformative Shift in Energy Landscape

In the coming year, solar power plants are set to play a significant role in Armenias energy landscape, constituting a noteworthy 12 percent of the total electricity production. The latest data reveals a promising trend, with solar energy contributing 30.1 percent to the overall production in July 2023 alone. This highlights the untapped potential of solar energy, accounting for 9.3 percent of the total production in the first nine months of 2023. For Armenia, heavily reliant on imported fossil fuels, embracing solar power offers a decentralized energy source, reducing dependency on external suppliers, enhancing energy security, and mitigating vulnerabilities to geopolitical tensions and supply disruptions.

Furthermore, the annual production forecast for 2023 anticipates that solar electricity will constitute 12 percent of the total production, reflecting the growing significance of solar energy in the national energy mix. The forecasts for 2024 vary, underscoring the need for continued exploration and discussion. Emphasizing the critical role of solar power in reducing dependence on expensive imported gas, this shift aligns with Armenias strategic objectives for sustainable energy development.

The trajectory of solar electricity production in Armenia appears poised for exponential growth, with forecasts indicating that it could potentially contribute 20 percent of the electricity generation by 2024, surpassing hydropower. However, this surge in demand for solar energy also underscores the importance of updating the electrical infrastructure to handle a potential doubling of supply and demand, ensuring a resilient and sustainable energy future for Armenia.
